<!DOCTYPE exercise.pack
  SYSTEM "../Symbols.dtd">
<exercise.pack xmlns="Compositor"
               xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
               id="Test_Hyperplanes"
               xsi:schemaLocation="Compositor file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle2.5/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Compositor.xsd">
	  <texsupport href="../LinearAlgebraTeXSupport.xml"/>
	  <title>Distance of Point from Hyperplane: Self Test</title>
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>For each of the statements below about a point <math>
                     <latex>P</latex>
                  </math> and hyperplane <math>
                     <latex>H</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> indicate if it is true or false</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> always lies on <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This is false.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This is false. – To see this recall that there is some nonzero vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{n}\neq 0</latex>
                        </math>, and a number <math>
                           <latex>c</latex>
                        </math> such that <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> belongs to the hyperplane exactly when</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{n} }{ \Vect{x} } = c</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>But then <math>
                           <latex>s := \Abs{ \Vect{n} } \neq 0</latex>
                        </math>. So the equation</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>t\cdot s</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>c</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>has the unique solution <math>
                           <latex>t = c/s</latex>
                        </math>. Therefore, <math>
                           <latex>t\cdot \Vect{n}</latex>
                        </math> does not lie on <math>
                           <latex>H</latex>
                        </math> so long as <math>
                           <latex>t\neq c/s</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> always has distance <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math> from <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This is false.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This is false. – <math>
                           <latex>P</latex>
                        </math> has distance <math>
                           <latex>0</latex>
                        </math> from <math>
                           <latex>H</latex>
                        </math> exactly when <math>
                           <latex>P</latex>
                        </math> lies on <math>
                           <latex>H</latex>
                        </math>. However, we just found in the previous problem that not every point in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math> lies on <math>
                           <latex>H</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>The distance from <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> to <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math> is <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math> exactly when <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> lies on <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This is true!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The distance from <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> to <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math> is only defined if any two points of <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math> have the same distance from <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This is false.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This is false. – The distance from <math>
                           <latex>P</latex>
                        </math> to <math>
                           <latex>H</latex>
                        </math> is always defined.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The distance from <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> to <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math> is the distance of <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> from all points of <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This is false.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This is false. – There is always exactly one point on <math>
                           <latex>H</latex>
                        </math> which is closest to <math>
                           <latex>P</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The distance from <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> to <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math> is the distance from <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> to the point of <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math> closest to <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If the distance from <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> to <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math> is <math>
                        <latex>d</latex>
                     </math>, then</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Dstnc{P}{Q}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\geq</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>d</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>for every <math>
                        <latex>Q</latex>
                     </math> on <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If the distance from <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> to <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math> is negative, then <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> lies on the other side of <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>This sentence does not make any sense.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If the distance from <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> to <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math> is positive, then <math>
                        <latex>P</latex>
                     </math> does not lie on <math>
                        <latex>H</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Correct! – The distance from <math>
                           <latex>P</latex>
                        </math> to <math>
                           <latex>H</latex>
                        </math> is the distance from <math>
                           <latex>P</latex>
                        </math> to the point on <math>
                           <latex>H</latex>
                        </math> closest to <math>
                           <latex>P</latex>
                        </math>. If this distance is positive, this means that <math>
                           <latex>P</latex>
                        </math> does not lie on <math>
                           <latex>H</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
</exercise.pack>
